<Layout title="About | TechZeph" description="About TechZeph, the portfolio direction, and the kind of work this site will collect.">
  <PageIntro kicker="/about" title="A practical portfolio for technical and creative project work." description="I’m Elliot Harrison, a self-taught developer and technical learner building under the name TechZeph." />
  <SectionBand>
    <div class="tz-container tz-prose-layout">
      <aside><p class="tz-kicker">01 / About me</p></aside>
      <article>
        <h2 class="tz-serif mb-12 text-4xl leading-[.95] tracking-[-.04em] sm:text-6xl">Building skill in public, one project at a time.</h2>
        <div class="tz-prose">
          <p>My background is not a traditional computer science route. I came from working as a chef, where I learned how to operate under pressure, solve practical problems quickly, lead teams, and keep systems moving even when things became chaotic. Over time, that same interest in systems, structure, and problem-solving pulled me towards technology.</p>
          <p>My current focus is on cybersecurity, Linux, web development, AI tooling, and local-first systems. I’m especially interested in how people can use technology to become more capable, independent, and creative without being locked into bloated platforms or tools they don’t fully understand.</p>
          <p>TechZeph is where I document that process. I use this site as a personal archive for the things I’m learning, building, breaking, fixing, and refining. Some of that work is practical: websites, scripts, automation, development environments, security labs, and AI-assisted workflows. Some of it is exploratory: operating systems, local language models, digital autonomy, open-source tooling, and better ways to organise knowledge.</p>
          <p>I’m not trying to present myself as a finished expert. The aim is to create useful things, understand them properly, and slowly build a technical foundation strong enough to support larger ideas.</p>
          <p>The kind of work I enjoy sits between creativity and infrastructure. I like clean interfaces, practical tools, resilient systems, and technology that gives people more control over their own lives. I’m drawn to projects that combine design, security, automation, AI, and education.</p>
          <p>At the moment, I’m focused on improving my technical depth, building a stronger portfolio, and creating systems that help me learn, work, and think more clearly. Over time, I want TechZeph to become more than a portfolio: a living archive of experiments, tools, notes, and projects built around useful technology, digital independence, and thoughtful design.</p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </SectionBand>
</Layout>
